<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06026141 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06026141 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CAMPBELL; STUDENT; PROTEST; PLANNING; CLOSING; HIGH-SCHOOL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The pending battle over which two of Campbell Union High School District's sixcampuses must close could tear the community apart as parents, students andschool officials clash.;    &quot;It's going to get into a 'Close theirs -- notmine,' &quot; said Mike Thompson, a parent and unsuccessful candidate for the boardof trustees. &quot;They're going to get the kids mad at each other.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SCHOOLS EXPECT HOSTILITYCAMPBELL FACES CLASH ON CLOSINGS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     More than a decade ago, the district was shaken by emotionally chargeddecisions to close Camden and Campbell high schools.;    &quot;I think it's goingto divide the community now more than it did before,&quot; said trustee LouisMarotti, who at Thursday night's board meeting joined trustee RoderickMacDermott on the losing end of a 3-2 vote to close two campuses.;    SusanBageley, a parent at Prospect High who has been active in district politics,said she and others plan to pull their children from the Campbell district andenroll them in private schools because of the vote.;    School officials vowto do their best to minimize infighting.;    &quot;We're going to do everythingpossible to avoid that,&quot; said Gail Long, the district's public informationofficer.;    School officials have scheduled public hearings at each of thesix high schools before their vote, scheduled for Feb. 28, on which twocampuses to close. Originally, only two hearings were planned -- one for thethree schools west of Highway 17 and another for the three to the east.;    AtThursday night's board meeting, about 400 people packed the Leigh High Schoolcafeteria to hear a consultant's report and public comment on a series ofspending cuts proposed to save the district from bankruptcy. But by the timethe board voted, almost four hours after the meeting started, many had left.;   Tempers flared among those who remained when the board refused to vote thatnight on which schools to close, with people shouting for the trustees to makea decision so that students and schools could begin to plan for next year.;   In interviews Friday, trustees said they had not decided which schools toclose, although it appears likely they will select one on each side of Highway17. Trustees and school officials were reluctant even to discuss which schoolsthey thought should close.;    School board members said they'll examine manyissues before deciding, including the number of students affected, programsavailable at the sites, capacities at each school, the district's ethnicbalance, and the value of the sites if put to alternate uses -- for example,if leased out.;    Teachers have been among the main advocates ofconsolidation to four schools. Their association president said he was pleasedwith the decision, even though it could mean layoffs.;    &quot;Overriding that isthe ability to do our jobs well,&quot; said Campbell Education Associationpresident Steve Matusow.;    The district expects a $5 million shortfall nextyear, and the staff has asked the board to make at least $3.2 million in cuts.Closing two schools will save about half that amount, and the staff says othermeasures also must be taken, possibly including cutting athletic programs andincreasing the number of students per teacher.; IF YOU'RE INTERESTEDHearingswill be held at 7 p.m. in the school cafeterias at Blackford on Feb. 4, DelMar on Feb. 6, Westmont on Feb. 7, Prospect on Feb. 12, Leigh on Feb. 14 andBranham on Feb. 21. The board expects to vote Feb. 28 on which schools will beclosed.; SCHOOLS AT RISK; Campbell Union High School District plans to closetwo of its six campuses to save money. A decision on which must close isexpected next month.; (box)Blackford High School, 3800 Blackford Ave., SanJose. Enrollment: 916; (box)Branham High School, 1570 Branham Lane, San Jose.Enrollment: 973; (box)Del Mar High School, 1224 Del Mar Ave., San Jose.Enrollment: 1,086; (box)Leigh High School, 5210 Leigh Ave., San Jose.Enrollment: 1,026; (box)Prospect High School, 18900 Prospect Road, Saratoga.Enrollment: 957; (box)Westmont High School, 4805 Westmont Ave., Campbell.Enrollment: 867; Source: School district  </TEXT><BYLINE>  ALETA PAYNE, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910126  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  662  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday January 26, 199100026141,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>